    <subexercises>
      <title>Challenge</title>
      <exercise>
        <webwork>
          <pg-code>
            $m = random(5,15,1);
            $n = $m + random(10,20,1);
            $p = random(50,100,5);
            $answerb = $p-1;
            $q = random(500,2000,50);
            $answerc = $q-1;
          </pg-code>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>x^{<var name="$m"/>}\cdot x^{a}=x^{<var name="$n"/>}</m>, where <m>a</m> is a
                natural number. How many possibilities are there for <m>a</m>?
              </p>
              <p>
                <var name="'1'" width="10"/>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p>
                Let <m>x^{<var name="$m"/>}\cdot x^{a}=x^{<var name="$n"/>}</m>. Then <m>a</m> must
                be <m><var name="$n"/>-<var name="$m"/></m>. So there is only one possibility for
                <m>a</m>.
              </p>
            </solution>
          </task>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>x^{b}\cdot x^{c}=x^{<var name="$p"/>}</m>, where <m>b</m> and <m>c</m> are
                natural numbers. How many possibilities are there for <m>b</m>?
              </p>
              <p>
                <var name="$answerb" width="10"/>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p>
                Let <m>x^{b}\cdot x^{c}=x^{<var name="$p"/>}</m>. Many possibilities exist for
                <m>b</m> and <m>c</m>. Since <m>b</m> and <m>c</m> must be natural numbers, let's
                start with <m>b</m> equal to <m>1</m>. Then <m>c</m> must equal <var name="$p-1"/>,
                because <m>x^{1}\cdot x^{<var name="$p-1"/>}=x^{<var name="$p"/>}</m>. Considering
                all of the possibilities for <m>b</m>, notice that <m>b</m> can equal
                <m>1,2,3,\ldots,<var name="$p-1"/></m>. Therefore, there are <var name="$p-1"/>
                possibilities for <m>b</m>. Note that <m>b</m> can't equal <var name="$p"/> because
                that would force <m>c</m> to be zero,which is not a natural number.
              </p>
            </solution>
          </task>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>x^{d}\cdot x^{e}=x^{<var name="$q"/>}</m> where <m>d</m> and <m>e</m> are
                natural numbers. How many possibilities are there for <m>d</m>?
              </p>
              <p>
                <var name="$answerc" width="10"/>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p>
                Let <m>x^{d}\cdot x^{e}=x^{<var name="$q"/>}</m>. Many possibilities exist for
                <m>d</m> and <m>e</m>. Since <m>d</m> and <m>e</m> must be natural numbers, let's
                start with <m>d</m> equal to <m>1</m>. Then <m>e</m> must equal <var name="$q-1"/>,
                because <m>x^{1}\cdot x^{<var name="$q-1"/>}=x^{<var name="$q"/>}</m>. Considering
                all of the possibilities for <m>d</m>, notice that <m>d</m> can equal
                <m>1,2,3,\ldots,<var name="$q-1"/></m>. Therefore, there are <var name="$q-1"/>
                possibilities for <m>d</m>. Note that <m>d</m> can't equal <var name="$q"/> because
                that would force <m>e</m> to be zero, which is not a natural number.
              </p>
            </solution>
          </task>
        </webwork>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <webwork>
          <pg-macros>
            <macro-file>parserPopUp.pl</macro-file>
          </pg-macros>
          <pg-code>
            $m = random(2,3,1);
            $mraised = 100*$m;
            $p = random(4,5,1);
            $praised = 100*$p;
            $less = DropDown(['&lt;','>','='],0);
            $more = DropDown(['&lt;','>','='],1);
            $equal = DropDown(['&lt;','>','='],2);
            if ($m**$p == $p**$m) {$popup = $equal;}
            else {
              $popup = ($m**$p > $p**$m) ? $more : $less;
            };
          </pg-code>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Choose the correct inequality or equal sign to make the relation true.
            </p>
            <p>
              <m><var name="$m"/>^{<var name="$praised"/>}</m> <var name="$popup" form="popup"/> <m><var name="$p"/>^{<var name="$mraised"/>}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              Trying to calculate <m><var name="$m"/>^{<var name="$praised"/>}</m> or
              <m><var name="$p"/>^{<var name="$mraised"/>}</m> results in very large numbers. Notice
              that
              <m><var name="$m"/>^{<var name="$praised"/>}=<var name="$m"/>^{(<var name="$p"/>\cdot 100)}</m>.
              Also, notice that
              <m><var name="$p"/>^{<var name="$mraised"/>}=<var name="$p"/>^{(<var name="$m"/>\cdot100)}</m>.
              So to know if
              <m><var name="$m"/>^{<var name="$praised"/>}</m> or
              <m><var name="$p"/>^{<var name="$mraised"/>}</m> is bigger, we only have to compare
              <m><var name="$m"/>^{<var name="$p"/>}</m> with
              <m><var name="$p"/>^{<var name="$m"/>}</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </webwork>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <webwork>
          <pg-code>
            do {
              $a = random(-15,-1,2);
              $b = random(-10,-2,2);
              $coefficient = $a + $b;
            } until ($coefficient &lt; -7);
            $ax = Formula("$a x")->reduce;
            $bx = Formula("$b x")->reduce;
            $complete = Formula("$coefficient*x")->reduce;
            $m = MultiAnswer($ax, $bx)->with(
            singleResult => 1,
              checker => sub {
                my ( $correct, $student, $self ) = @_;
                my ( $astu, $bstu ) = @{$student};
                my ( $acor, $bcor ) = @{$correct};
                if ( $astu == Formula("0")) {Value::Error('None of your values can be zero.')};
                if ( $bstu == Formula("0")) {Value::Error('None of your values can be zero.')};
                if ($astu+$bstu != $complete) {return 0;} else {return 1};
              }
            );
            do {
              $c = random(-15,-1,2);
              $d = random(-10,-2,2);
              $expx = random(15,30,5);
              $coefficient2 = $c + $d;
            } until ($coefficient2 &lt; -7);
            $cexp = Formula("$c*(x**$expx)")->reduce;
            $dexp = Formula("$d*(x**$expx)")->reduce;
            $complete2 = Formula("$coefficient2*(x**$expx)");
            $m2 = MultiAnswer($cexp, $dexp)->with(
            singleResult => 1,
              checker => sub {
                my ( $correct, $student, $self ) = @_;
                my ( $cstu, $dstu ) = @{$student};
                my ( $ccor, $dcor ) = @{$correct};
                if ( $cstu == 0) {Value::Error('None of your values can be zero.')};
                if ( $dstu == 0) {Value::Error('None of your values can be zero.')};
                if ($cstu+$dstu != $complete2) {return 0;} else {return 1};
              }
            );
            $p = list_random(2,3,5,7,11,13,17);
            $exp1 = random(20,50,5);
            $exp2 = random(10,30,10);
            $exp3 = $exp1 + $exp2;
            $expa = Formula("(x**$exp1)")->reduce;
            $expb = Formula("(x**$exp2)")->reduce;
            $num = Formula("$p");
            $complete3 = Formula("$num*(x**$exp3)");
            $m3 = MultiAnswer($num, $expa, $expb)->with(
            singleResult => 1,
              checker => sub {
                my ( $correct, $student, $self ) = @_;
                my ( $numstu, $expastu, $expbstu ) = @{$student};
                my ( $numcor, $expacor, $expbcor ) = @{$correct};
                if ( $numstu == 1) {Value::Error('None of your values can be one.')};
                if ( $expastu == 1) {Value::Error('None of your values can be one.')};
                if ( $expbstu == 1) {Value::Error('None of your values can be one.')};
                if ($numstu*$expastu*$expbstu != $complete3) {return 0;} else {return 1};
              }
            );
          </pg-code>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Fill in the blanks with algebraic expressions that make the equation true. You may
              not use <m>0</m> or <m>1</m> in any of the blank spaces. For example, if
              <m>\mathord{?}+\mathord{?}=8x</m>, then one possible answer is <m>3x+5x=8x</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
              There are infinitely many correct answers. <em>Be creative.</em> After finding a
              correct answer, see if you can come up with a different answer that is also correct.
            </p>
            <p>
              <ol marker="a.">
                <li>
                  <p>
                    <var name="$m" width="6"/><m>{}+{}</m><var name="$m" width="6"/><m>{}=<var name="$complete"/></m>
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    <var name="$m2" width="6"/><m>{}+{}</m><var name="$m2" width="6"/><m>{}=<var name="$complete2"/></m>
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    <var name="$m3" width="6"/><m>{}\cdot{}</m><var name="$m3" width="6"/><m>{}\cdot{}</m><var name="$m3" width="6"/><m>{}=<var name="$complete3"/></m>
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              <ol marker="a.">
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Think about adding like terms. One possibility is:
                    <m><var name="$ax"/> + <var name="$bx"/> = <var name="$complete"/></m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Think about adding like terms. One possibility is:
                    <m><var name="$cexp"/> + <var name="$dexp"/> = <var name="$complete2"/></m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Think about multiplying exponents. One possibility is:
                    <m><var name="$num"/> \cdot <var name="$expa"/> \cdot <var name="$expb"/> = <var name="$complete3"/></m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </webwork>
      </exercise>
